at|mitche: Bidding:  3@c in second seat is not a good idea for several reasons:  
First, South has an outside 4 card major.  You risk missing easy games in 4@h when you open 3@C.
Second, with 2 aces, South has defensive values.
Third, with only 6 clubs, South cannot stand to be tapped more than once, unless he gets lucky -- So better is to pass. 
Sometimes 3@c will work well, but for every time it does, you'll be losing points unnecessarily at least twice as often.
And probably the most important reason for not bidding 3@c on this type of hand: it destroys your partner's confidence 
in your bidding.  |
